column1: Between 24 December 2021 and 31 March 2022, what will be the highest seven-day average for COVID-19 patients in the UK to be admitted to [a] hospital?
column5: ['Less than 1,500', 'Between 1,500 and 2,000, inclusive', 'More than 2,000 but less that 2,500', 'Between 2,500 and 3,000, inclusive', 'More than 3,000 but less than 3,500', 'Between 3,500 and 4,000, inclusive', 'More than 4,000']
column6: ['Technology', 'Society', 'Health', 'Non-US Politics']
My previous update was probably an overcorrection, and recent data suggests the average will not break 2500. It's just not QUITE keeping pace.

As @belikewater says below, this now looks like it will fall a little short using the averaging. Admissions in Scotland started falling just over a week ago and that will help prevent the UK total reaching 2,500

With the caveat that I don’t entirely understand how to parse the data issue and the lag/forward look, this is going to be close. Also, retroactive data revisions happen a lot with Covid numbers. High uncertainty.

This could be really close if we used the UKHSA definition of the 7-day average, but we're not. 2218.6 on March 25. 277 added in the past week. 2218.6 + 277 = 2495.6. And that would include 1 extra day of data. It looks likely to be just under 2500. I'm going to have a bad Brier score on this question.

This is largely based on intuition, but current numbers suggest I should update my earlier forecast for a higher probability of breaking 2500. A highly qualitative look at the shape of the curve makes it look as though it won't break 2500, but I don't have high confidence.
Today's data suggests that the 7-day average will likely be just under 2500.

It's quite possible that the daily numbers are already over 2500 for the last few (not yet reported) days, which makes it very possible that we will get into bin 4 before the 31st. Scotland is going through its worst covid wave so it should see at least the same growth, if not more, as England on the days where we only have data for England. The next update after this weekend will be key.

Thanks to @paulm who reminded me that there's more data for England available before it's available for all of the UK, and that this question could be very close. If hospital admissions grow at the same pace from March 23-30 as they did from March 16-23, then the UK would end up at 2502 on March 30. I had thought that case growth had been slowing, but that may not be true, as everything I've read (including @paulm's comment below) suggests that cases may be even higher now than they were at the peak of Omicron. So, I'll go 50/50 on bins 3/4 for now. (Either way, I'm not going to have a good Brier score on this question, lol.)

I think daily admissions will be over 2,500 on 31st, but how high the 7-day average will be is a little harder to gauge: based on the clarification above I think it will be 2,425-2,525. With erratic case reporting, phasing out of LFT availability and half the testing rate that we had in a January, the updates tomorrow afternoon should be quite telling. While case numbers appear to have peaked I’m starting to think a truer representation of severe cases are hospitalisation, and that should trend upwards for at least 7-10 days. Anecdotally I know of more families that have had at least one covid case this month than the last two combined.

The question states that, "The outcome will be determined using 7-day average data as reported by the UK Health Security Agency." The 7-day averages reported by the UKHSA for a given date are derived from data from 3 days before that date through 3 days after that date. However, GJO has just issued a clarification that they will use 7-day averages calculated normally from UKHSA daily data; i.e., GJO will consider the 7-day average for a given date to be derived from data from 6 days before that date through that date. So, in effect, the question will be determined using data through March 31 instead of April 3. As cases still seem to be growing, it seems likely that the (true) 7-day average of hospital admissions will still be growing as of March 31. However, as growth in hospital admissions seems to be slowing, it looks unlikely to me that a 7-day average of 2500 will be reached in the remainder of the forecast period.

On Jan. 2, I wrote, "I think this question will likely just be about the Omicron wave, and the peak of hospitalizations should be long past by March 31." Indeed, the Omicron peak is long past. But unfortunately, even though an enormous fraction of the UK population just had Omicron, a new, enormous fraction is now getting BA.2 (which really deserves its own letter, and frankly should have been named "Pi" on March 14). The BA.2 wave is sweeping through the UK more slowly than did Omicron, perhaps because of existing immunity and warming weather. ZOE Covid data supposedly suggest that UK cases are at an all-time high, while UKHSA data suggest that cases are nearing a peak in the UK that is far below, perhaps ~60% below, the Omicron peak. The growth in hospital admissions has started to slow, which also suggests that cases are somewhere near a peak. So it looks to me like both cases and hospitalizations may be nearing their peaks, and it looks most likely to me that the peak of the BA.2 hospital admissions wave may end up below that of the Omicron wave. I wonder whether UK data have reached a turning point, where such a small proportion of cases continues to be tested officially that it is difficult to tell the relative sizes of Covid waves and when or whether a peak has been reached. This is going to make a lot of things more difficult for everyone.

I had been puzzled as to why the curve for the 7-day MA stops 3 days before the last reported day, thus implying that the reported MA does not include the 3 last dates. I mean, why not start counting from the last reported day, and go 6 days back, so that to calculate the latest 7-day MA?

"ZOE COVID Study estimates daily coronavirus cases in the UK are at a record-high, but official figures are much lower amid a drop in testing" https://twitter.com/BNODesk/status/1507411236765450272 I'm not sure what to think here.

I'm leaning increasingly towards the belief that hospitalizations are levelling off below 2,500. This is really hard to judge though, and my conclusion doesn't fit well with the ZOE COVID data (which shows cases still climbing fast, including in older age groups; more hospitalizations ought to follow). So my confidence is low right now.
I neglected this question a bit, but it looks like it will stay under 2500. Still, shifting from 100% to put 5% on over 2,500 because it's hard to be certain with the data lag.
It's not looking like admissions will reach past 2500/day, as cases look like they may be getting close to a peak.

We may be close to the peak of cases over the next few days, for England and Scotland. With hospitalisation following ~6 days later we could end up around 2,400 or so before the 7-day average starts to flatten again. Hard to be specific on this one.

3 more days data just appeared. While [7 day average] hospitalizations per day are high and still increasing, the gradient appears to have levelled off ever so slightly. Its not much, but crucially it didn't just get steeper.

Minor update; after checking again I think it is still not conclusive, but will be very close as a 7-day average. We may see a few days above 2,500 within the timeframe but I’m not sure if the average will reach bin 3.
Hospitalization data only goes up to 15/03/22 and is in a roughly linear climb. Extrapolating that gets me 2,682.36 hospitalizations on 31/03/22 (i.e. beyond 2,500). Others have said similar.
Updating based perspective from other forecasters. Still cautious about surpassing 2500, but less so.
As per comments via @alh below

@belikewater @paulm @Will-Roberts @ctsats and others who have given a (variable) amount of weight to bin 4, are there reasons aside from extrapolating from current data to believe that the current wave of hospitalisations should surpass the original Omicron wave? I understand the concerns about waning immunity from vaccines, relaxation of the rules, and so on, but these were also concerns around the first Omicron waves and the current growth in hospitalisations is much more horizontal than the first Omicron wave (depending on where you set the start dates of course).

This is the best forecast I can make at the moment but I have a relatively low participation rate on this question. It's one of those questions I had wished I monitored. In the grand scheme of things, I think I made the right decision because I am now busier than I have ever been in the last decade. So just because I miss this question does not mean I made the wrong decision, perhaps.

Spikes in hospitalization appear to grow close to a linear rate, with some acceleration, as seen in the December spike- once the spike gets going, it accelerates a little, but not a lot. At current rate UK is adding 33-35 hospitalizations per day to the average, on average. At this rate it will not cross the 2500 threshold, but it will come quite close. Would need to add just over 39 hospitalizations to the average each day on average in order to cross this threshold. A real possibility, but an underdog.

This could be very close. I wasn't paying close enough attention to their BA.2 wave. March 11: 1718.4. 341 added in the past week. 2.86 weeks to go. If growth were linear, we'd see 1718.4 + 341*2.86 = 2693.7. Growth may be close to linear for a while, and it all also depends on when case growth slows down. As there's no sign that cases are slowing down yet (in the UK or other parts of Europe), and hospital admissions lag cases by about a week, I'm hedging higher on bin 4. If cases keep growing like they are currently for a few more days, then hospital admissions will be baked in and will likely exceed a 7-day average of 2500.

BA.2 at 32% in the UK a couple of weeks ago according to UK variant distribution data: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-variants-genomically-confirmed-case-numbers/variants-distribution-of-case-data-11-march-2022 And perhaps around 75% as of now according to: https://outbreak.info/location-reports?xmin=2022-01-01&xmax=2022-03-18&loc=GBR Combine this with the Government's laissez-faire approach (no need to wear a mask, test, or isolate if positive) and community transmission is now spreading into the middle- and upper-age groups where immunity is perhaps starting to wane and hospitalisation is clearly increasing. The big question is whether the peak reaches higher than in January when we had over 200k cases/day, but given the new conditions it looks worryingly possible.

7-day MA at 1654 as of Mar 10, steadily gaining ~50/day for the previous 3-4 days. Last data of Mar 13 at 1777 new hospitalizations. If this increase in the rate is maintained (let alone increased), it will exceed 2500 before the end of March. BA.2 is the obvious suspect, which has been wrecking havoc in HK (https://twitter.com/DrEricDing/status/1500988988722749447 , different conditions there though). Add the relaxation of measures, and...

With the new BA.2 wave taking off, and potentially waning immunity in older age groups, I think its time we acknowledge that surpassing 2,500 hospitalizations per day in the near future is a distinct possibility. That said, the slope in hospitalizations is still relatively gentle at the moment and there's only a few weeks left on the question.
Hospitalizations seem to rise again due to BA2 omicron variant: https://twitter.com/DrEricDing/status/1500983875207680006
Narrowing my forecast further as there's not so much time left for anything unexpected to happen.
Don't follow me, I'm following the crowd on this one.

Official cases are falling, hospitalizations are falling, and estimates of true cases (thought to be much higher) are also beginning to fall now. Also less time left for something unexpected to happen since my last forecast.
Cases consistently decreasing. Most recent numbers are 1,456 for 7 day average. Highest was in the 2,260s in January.
Looks like it peaked early in January and has been going down since the highest of just over 2200.

We're now well past peak hospitalizations (2,298.4 on 01/01/22) and cases, though they aren't down anywhere near as much as I'd like, are stable. I still wouldn't rule out a second peak due to BA.2 or some other new variant / event, but its looking increasingly unlikely that would push us over 2,500 before the end of March.

I'm waiting for today's update, which will revise previous numbers upwards a little. Depending on how the numbers look, I'll revise this forecast up or down. Given that the recent peak was 2,298, if numbers were revised upwards by 8.8%, then we will tip into bin 4. I really don't have a feel for what percentage of recent cases have been reinfections, and I don't think it's super likely that it's that many, but we'll have to see. A lot of people have been reinfected.

Data bomb here. They're changing case definitions in the UK, to change how infections are counted. They have not been counting reinfections! And now, they're only going to count reinfections that occur >= 90 days after a previous infection. That's ridiculous. A lot of people are getting reinfected with Omicron a month after a first infection. This must also have affected Covid hospital admissions data, because an admission due to reinfection wouldn't have been counted if the case wasn't counted.
Seems that the current wave is passed and if somethings else were to turn up any other level would have a reasonable shot of being reached.
The UK government announcement that most measures against COVID-19 will be dropped on 27 January 2022 and SARS-CoV-2 will henceforth be treated like a seasonal flu.

"“Very early observations from India and Denmark suggest there is no dramatic difference in severity compared to BA.1,” tweeted Tom Peacock, a virologist at Imperial College, London, adding the latest variant should not call into question the effectiveness of existing vaccines. Peacock stressed, “We do not currently have a strong handle on … how much more transmissibility BA.2 might have over BA.1. However, we can make some guesses/early observations.” “There is likely to be minimal differences in vaccine effectiveness against BA.1 and BA.2. Personally, I’m not sure BA.2 is going to have a substantial impact on the current Omicron wave of the pandemic,” he added." https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/1/22/omicron-sub-variant-throws-up-new-virus-questions

A BA.2 surge is coming, but I don't know how big it will be. Denmark offers an interesting comparison. Given that hospitalizations remain high currently, it's possible that BA.2 could soon tip them even higher. https://twitter.com/Gab_H_R/status/1485067562291453952 Or, I could well end up with a horrible Brier score on this question... @paulm

Increasing weight on bin 4: BA.2 + virus working its way through older segments of the population. Hospitalizations have decreased very little in the elderly, are holding steady among children and are increasing among school-age children in England. BA.2 has yet to hit the UK. https://www.ilpandacentrostudio.it/uk.html
No other vagues before end of March

Case rates are now half the 7-day peak of 183k just two weeks ago. Daily hospitalisation is declining, but much more slowly, likely due to the gradual spread through older age-groups after transmission through <30 yrs over Christmas and the New Year. This decline looks set for now, and it does look very unlikely to get beyond the earlier peak for at least the next few weeks, but it's not a certainty that things could change during February or beyond. Not yet ruling out other eventualities causing a small second wave, but this will probably be lower than the first and more drawn out in my view.
Last 7 day reported was Jan 7 with 2243, high for the last week was 2426 on Jan 10, cases are on the down slope, still looking promising

Yes there could be another variant and if that happens I will revise my forecast. But if we look at lead time for Omicron to peak (based on what it looks like now) it is still 2 months from Mid Nov to mid Jan, which, projecting forward from today, assuming there was another variant starting to take off now, it would take us well into March and close to the deadline. And that would require the next variant to be as infectious. We will see, but for is I’m taking the view that no new variant of concern will pop up in the next few weeks and it would take some time to circulate and cause serious illness, taking the peak of hospitalisations out after end March.
Looks like it's peaked and plateaued while UK cases are pretty quickly falling.

Hospitalisation is just starting to fall, and the average should follow within a few days, from 2,242 on 7th Jan. I think the decline in cases will slow and spread towards older populations, and still expect a plateauing or even a slight rise over the next few weeks, but it's hard to gauge. I think two factors will help determine this; the first is that prior infections were far higher leading up to Omicron compared to Delta - perhaps 17M total cases in the preceding 5 months (5.7M recorded), compared to 5M (1.7M recorded) in the same period before Delta - so the susceptible proportion of the population is substantially reduced this time. The second is the 53%+ third dose coverage, which significantly restores immunity, and slightly reduces transmissibility. From the data supplied by @belikewater below, it looks like transmission may take 6-8 weeks to spread through children and young adults into older age groups. After 6-8 wks in the Delta wave there was a roughly 15% net increase increase in hospitalisation/case, perhaps related to this effect. Omicron will be moving into more highly vaccinated populations (the third dose uptake increases roughly 10% per decade in age), and this could result in a lower increase in daily hospitalisation this time round. I'm starting to think we'll see increasing numbers of people staying in hospital while daily intake remains slightly lower, but not with any great confidence yet.

Some plateau for now but not much mixing going on. People keeping to family groups and being careful. Shops and resturants are closing due to lack of staff. Almost lockdown levels of interaction. When school goes back admissions should increase
I still think it's possible that hospital admissions could tip into bin 4 over the next few days, but bin 3 is looking more likely after all. I was most likely quite wrong on much of this forecast.

I'm leaving a tiny amount on the higher bins not for Omicron but for a new variant. We first heard of Omicron in late Nov, and it's causing a peak in hospitalizations less than 2 months later. The chance that a similarly contagious but more virulent new variant will pop up and cause another wave in this forecast period is very small but not zero.
Starting to think I could have stuck with original forecast (it wouldn’t be the first time...) https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1374486
Looks like the peak has sustained and hospitalizations are starting to come down a bit. Leaving some chance of a second surge in the timeframe but 2k to 2.5k looks likely to be the peak.
Looking more and more stable so upping bin 3 odds. With 2 months left until resolution I'm still nervous about something coming out of left field though

Following @belikewater for three reasons: (1) This comment https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1381895; (2) Amazing ratio of Brier to median of 0.7247 over 99 questions (I don't have data on how many of these have been scored) (3) Fellow Bruce Lee fan. I'm wondering how practicing martial arts might correlate with forecasting ability. Are you perchance a practitioner as well as a fan?
It looks like we've peaked at 2,277.1, though I won't rule out a second peak or even another new variant before the end of March.
Looks like cases have peaked and hospitalizations may have peaked as well. Coming down and putting more weight on the 2k to 2.5k bucket.
Actually revising this to be even more heavy on bin 3.

Looking more and more like the early January data is not the result of any discrepency, and like hospitalisations are in fact not increasing by any measurable amount right now. Also, looking at the demographics of cases from 1st Jan -> 4th Jan in England it seems that cases are relatively static in the over 60s 'at risk' group. It looks like the boosters are extremely effective against Omicron. I now feel that with case numbers starting to decline ~ 10 days ago that we are firmly more likely to stay in bin 3.

I still expect hospitalizations to increase as Omicron makes its way through older segments of the population, but it looks likely that cases have already peaked, so the higher bins are looking less likely.
Cases and hospitalizations are both lower than I would have thought.

Adjusting up on bin 4 from my previous forecast (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1380349). The peak around new years hasn't had time to increase hospitalisations yet, so there should be an increase coming soon-ish. On the other hand, the downward trend in cases and still fairly low hospitalisation rates make me a bit more doubtful about crossing the 3000 line over a 7-day average. This week and early next week will be key to deciding the question imho.

Case numbers are still declining in England. While I'm still expecting them to rise from next week, they may well not rise enough to push the average hospitalisations much beyond 2,500 from this lower level, so I'm backing off from the original est of around 2,700-3,850 and waiting to see what happens to transmission next week. Previous comments here: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1381493

@belikewater Dialing down on my forecast. Earlier forecast was based on the assumption that even if we see the likelihood of hospitalizations be 1/3rd of earlier covid cases, we should be close to the 4000 mark considering the average number of cases now is 3x higher than the Alpha wave last year. Now rethinking this because 1> The absolute case numbers are flattening out 2> The Hospitalizations rate looks is almost 20% of the earlier covid wave. https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/hospitalisation-risk-omicron-around-one-third-delta-uk-analysis-shows-2021-12-31/

Admissions in England for 8 Jan are back below 2k as as they make up the majority of admissions the total might not be much over 2k when the weekly Scotland data is published. This means the daily average is going to plateau, putting less likelihood on the higher bins.

I had expected a lull in cases after New Year, but they have fallen further than I expected. I'm going to backtrack and see if they climb back to the expected level around 180-205k over the next few days as a result on schools and higher education's staggered openings gradually add to transmission. Till then I'm being a little more circumspect about numbers as younger age groups are not as likely to require hospitalisation.
Cases may be peaking lower than I expected.

As of 9 Jan, the daily count is already 2400 hospitalised. First two answers are therefore already impossible. Third answer highly unlikely because of continued rise. Previous daily peak was just above 4000. Against the current wave breaching 4000 is the fact that omicron causes proportionately fewer hospitalisation and that uptake of booster vaccinations has been brisk, AND the current vaccines offer good protection against hospitalisation. However, the total number of omicron cases is likely to easily breach the peak seen at the delta wave AND the doubling time is only three days compared to three weeks for delta which means that even if the total number of cases is smaller than delta, they will be much more bunched up.

Omicron still hasn't worked its way through older segments of the population. As they are infected, more will be admitted both because of and with Covid. Shifting my forecast slightly towards the last 2 bins.

Rethinking. I was worrying about a majority of England outside London seeing peaks at least as large as last year, and surges in hospitalizations as older segments of the population get infected, but I think those considerations might be misplaced. I suspect some trusts outside London may see very high rates, but not universally so. Now projecting a peak of ~3200-3500, about 75%-83% of last year's peak. I think @paulm is right. The 7-day average for Dec 31 for the UK was 2259. There were 2434 admissions on Jan 3. Cases are still rising. Bin 3 will probably be ruled out with Jan 6-10 data (as reflected in the 7-day average that's calculated for the date 3 days before).

Case rates are likely to track higher over the next two/three weeks I believe. Fastest growth in cases is around the North of England, and a recent UKHSA report indicates high transmission through sixth formers and university students. Uni terms don't tend to start till next Monday, so I think there is an opportunity for further spread connected to this. Further community transmission through to older age groups should gradually impact numbers and hospitalisation.
Cases and hospitalizations look like they may be leveling off a bit, bringing it down to put more weight on the 2k to 3k range.

I'm starting to think the last bin might be most likely. A couple forecasters made polar forecasts on that bin, and a few people have made single forecasts that are high on that bin. Kudos to @SE_Meyer and @DNK89, who have consistently been high or relatively high on that bin. I suspect I haven't been high enough on that bin. I'm not yet sure where the forecast will end up, but the data are currently suggesting that the risk of hospitalization with Omicron is ~20%-30% less than with Delta, and with cases far exceeding all previous peaks, things are likely not going to go very well.

After reading comments from @belikewater I'm inclined to change this again. Hospitalisations might look like they have peaked in London and seem to be levelling off nationwide, but I just can't work out why that would be the case, given that the figures show a small but defined drop between 30 and 31st December. I think there is either a reporting discrepency, or the lag effect of older age groups getting it has staggered for some reason. However if admissions don't start increasing over the next few days this looks less likely. Suggestions that hospitalisations in SA peaked at 63% of the delta peak gives some hope [https://twitter.com/rid1tweets/status/1478627119806750721/photo/1 ], but the dynamics are very different to the UK (vaccine rate, previous infection and age profile).
New data (30th Dec) shows a 7-day average of 2,182.9. The curve appears to have levelled at around 2,000 admissions per day, though its a little early to be confident it isn't going up further.
Avg is now over 2000 (2182.9 on the 30th and looking like it's come down slightly)
Assigning more weight to the last bin. https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/jan/06/hospitals-outside-london-expect-more-covid-patients-than-last-january
Seeing relatively good signs of a leveling off at this point, with admissions starting to drop in London, it gives more wiggle room for them to increase elsewhere and keep this number lower.
Well, bins 1 and 2 are now out! The 7-day average of hospitalizations for England on Dec 31 was >2000. I think bin 3 will be ruled out in the next few days.
Six days later and we have one more day of hospitalization data. :(
Last 7 days are showing hovering around 2k without the Scotland data, so the average will reach 2k this week, which rules out bins 1 and 2.
Cases are potentially peaking ~200k. Using my methodology from before [1] with a 1.5 to 1.75% hospitalization rate would get a range of 3,000 to 3,500. So I'm centering around that with wide tails.

With Omicron now at over 95% prevalence the relative level of hospitalisation should be reduced compared to the start of the Omicron surge when Delta was contributing a significant proportion of cases (ie through to mid-December). But transmission is now spreading into older age groups, with the rate of cases over 60+ years having roughly doubled in the last week. Cases are looking to remain at least 180-205k/day (yesterdays 218k count included an addition day of 20k from Wales I believe) for the next week, and I think could climb higher than this. Booster doses are steady around 60% of population and needing at least a week for efficacy. I'm now estimating a range of 2,850-3,750 based on cases plateauing over the next two weeks.

The 9:47 update on Jan 3 says "He says there are around 360 patients in hospital wards with Covid, about 10% of whom were in intensive care - a lower proportion than in previous waves." (https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-59857255) I'm pretty sure that's referring to London hospitals... which is no increase over the last week... which is interesting...

Omicron is moving very fast and trends coming from hot spots like London hint at a peak soon. Still the holiday gatherings full effect may not yet be showing so a lot can still happen in the next 2-4 weeks. https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/details/healthcare
I think this staying below 3000 is all about the effects of age on infection severity with Omicron.

Daily cases are now around 200,000 and while daily admissions to hospital have not been reported since 27th the total number in hospital has risen by close to 60% in less than a week. Given hospitalisation rates of c1.3-1.5% of cases, it seems unlikely now that the maximum average will be below 3,000. Distribution in the higher buckets is hard to assess while cases are still distorted by Xmas and NY processing so that its difficult to tell the rate of increases (and whether this is slowing. It is reported that cases in London have peaked and are falling but as a large numbe rof people go home and away from London for xmas I am not sure if this means that much.

Hospitalization data still only goes up to the 27th of December, but more data on cases is slowly coming through. Though we're past the phase of Omicron cases doubling every two days, they're still rising in the new data and exceeded 200K cases on the 29th of December.

If cases plateau around 200k as forecast last week, then a combination of younger age groups producing a lower level of hospitalisations may transition to older age groups (with higher hospitalisation) more smoothly, resulting in a lower peak, perhaps by the end of Jan. I think cases will climb slightly higher during middle of January but its hard to tell with a high degree of accuracy yet.

Unskewing this to be more centered around my estimate instead of weighted downward, looks like hospitalizations are certain to pass 1,500 and cases are going even higher than my ~175k upper bound guess.

There may be a lull now before the true peak. I’m expecting the 7-day average to reach 2,500/day in 10-14 days, but with the increase slowing as an effect of post-New Year caution including social distancing, and secondary schools reverting to mask wearing during term time. The lack of testing capability may also become a contributing factor shortly, and may hamper schools testing twice a week, making case counts less clear. Another concern is the spread into older age groups which looks to have started and will likely impact more quickly on rate of hospitalisation compared to the 15-45yrs ages that were more common over Christmas. Booster shots will help reduce severe symptoms but daily dose rates dropped back to pre-omicron levels after Dec 24th, with 59% now having had third dose.

Noting that the 7-day average on Dec 31 for patients in England calculated using the raw data provided on the resolution website is 1821.9, while cases in the UK continue to skyrocket. I expect a 7-day average of 2,000/day for the UK to be reached in the data for the first few days of January.
Todays latest average is already 1419, with all later days not yet showing in average as higher, so bin 1 is already out of the running.
Though the 7 day avg isn't past 1500 yet I'd be surprised not to see that happen

Greatly decreasing my forecast for 'Less than 1,500' as hospitalizations are currently at 1,419.6 and rising, looking likely to pass 1,500 soon. That said, I don't think the data is in line with worst case projections either so I've increased my forecasts for the lower bins above 1,500 the most. The truth may still be disguised by various data glitches over the Christmas period however.

There appears to be a substantially reduced risk of hospitalisation (potentially around 70%) from the Omicron variant, but it is significantly more infectious - infections are already three times as high as the Alpha variant peak and will likely rise further. However, London infections appear already to have peaked, and this is also what data from South Africa suggests is likely. With high vaccination levels now likely to prevent hospital admissions for a large proportion of the population, this suggests a peak that is significant, but well below that of January 2021, when it reached over 4000.
Reducing bin 1 a bit.

The UK government is preparing for a massive surge in hospitalizations: https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/nhs-england-makes-plans-for-field-hospitals-in-preparation-for-wave-of-omicron-covid-cases-1365680/amp "NHS leaders are planning for temporary field hospitals in hospital car parks and to review the capacity of their mortuaries in readiness for the expected surge of Covid patients over the next five weeks. There are a lot of moving parts to this question: * how high the peak in cases will be; this is a big question. * the lag from case identification to hospitalization, which is fairly diffuse and varies with location; it's generally 7-10 days. * how Omicron moves through different age groups in the population; Omicron has spread mainly in younger segments of the UK population so far. * the risk of hospitalization with Omicron, given the time of year and existing immunity profiles. * what restrictions will be put in place and for how long.

Initial analysis: - currently (data from 16th December) at 899 admissions and trending upwards; but assuming an ~14 day lag between cases and hospital admissions, we probably aren't looking at Omicron data yet. - we are already seeing daily results of over 100K cases, I expect a sharp Omicron peak of perhaps 200K-400K at the end of December, followed by a drop almost as quickly perhaps early January. - it looks like about 1 in 50 cases were being hospitalized mid-2021, and that rate has been falling (better medicine). There are reports of 50-70% fewer hospitalizations per case than previous variants (https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-59769969). So perhaps 1 in 100 to 1 in 200 cases will be hospitalized. - the hospitalizations peak is also likely to be more spread out than the cases peak. Perhaps another factor of 2 reduction in the hospital admissions peak? - unknown whether the base load of Delta (~900 admissions / day) will continue or drop, but I can't imagine it being competed out as fast as Omicron rises. - I haven't really considered beyond January. Time for further mutations or developments to occur.
